==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in the 1640's. From Latin ''[[abominatus]]'', past participle of ''[[abominari]]'' "to [[deprecate]] as [[ominous]]", "to [[abhor]]", "to curse"; derived from ''[[ab-]]'' "from" + ''[[omen]]'' "a [[foreboding]]".

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-abominate.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈbɒm.ə.ˌnəɪt/}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{obsolete}} [[abominable|Abominable]]; [[detest]]ed.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abominat|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To feel [[disgust]] towards; to [[abhor]]; to [[loathe]] or [[detest]] thoroughly; to [[hate]] in the highest degree, as if with religious [[dread]].
#: ''"Much as I '''abominate''' writing, I would not give up Mr. Collins's correspondence for any consideration."'' ([http://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Pride_and_Prejudice Pride and Prejudice])

